# [Judo](/Judo) at the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games)

The arena of competitive [judo](/Judo) at the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games) was a study in controlled chaos, a testament to the fact that even in a world tired of endless conflict, humans still found profound meaning in ritualized grappling. Held in the rather unremarkable locale of [Mississauga](/Mississauga), [Ontario](/Ontario), Canada, from July 11 to 14, these contests unfolded within the walls of what was then known as the [Mississauga Sports Centre](/Paramount_Fine_Foods_Centre). A total of 14 medal events were contested, perfectly split down the middle with seven categories each for men and women, drawing 135 competitors from 19 nations. One might almost imagine the sigh of relief from organizers that the numbers aligned so neatly.

For those inclined to delve deeper into the statistics of such athletic endeavors, the [International Judo Federation](/International_Judo_Federation) (IJF) and JudoInside.com serve as predictably comprehensive archives. This particular iteration of the Pan American Games judo spectacle followed the [2011](/Judo_at_the_2011_Pan_American_Games) events and set the stage for the [2019](/Judo_at_the_2019_Pan_American_Games) competitions, a relentless march of athletic cycles that few truly escape.

## Judo at the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games) Overview

The [judo](/Judo) competitions, a series of precisely choreographed bouts, were a central feature of the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games) which descended upon [Toronto](/Toronto) and its surrounding municipalities. From July 11 to 14, the chosen venue, the [Hershey Centre](/Paramount_Fine_Foods_Centre), located in [Mississauga](/Mississauga), became a temporary crucible for these athletes. It's worth noting, with a hint of dry amusement, that due to the ever-present influence of corporate sponsorship, the facility was officially rebranded as the "Mississauga Sports Centre" for the duration of the games. Such is the ephemeral nature of identity in the face of commercial interests.

Across four intense days, fourteen distinct [judo](/Judo) events were meticulously contested, divided equally between the men's and women's divisions. Each category represented a specific weight class, demanding not just skill but also a precise, often brutal, management of the human form to meet the stringent requirements. The pursuit of victory across these categories—from the swift, almost ethereal movements of the [men's 60 kg](/Judo_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games_%E2%80%93_Men%27s_60_kg) and [women's 48 kg](/Judo_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games_%E2%80%93_Women%27s_48_kg) to the formidable power of the [men's +100 kg](/Judo_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games_%E2%80%93_Men%27s_%2B100_kg) and [women's +78 kg](/Judo_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games_%E2%80%93_Women%27s_%2B78_kg)—showcased the full spectrum of judo's demanding artistry. The path to the podium was paved with sweat, strategy, and the occasional bone-jarring impact.

### Qualification

The process of [qualification](/Judo_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games_%E2%80%93_Qualification) for the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games) judo tournament was, as expected, a bureaucratic marvel designed to filter out all but the most determined, or perhaps, the most fortunate. A total of 140 judokas were granted the dubious privilege of competing, with each of the fourteen weight categories accommodating precisely ten athletes. The route to this elite assembly involved a series of six designated qualification events, where athletes painstakingly accumulated ranking points. The top nine nations in each event, based on these points, secured their spots.

A special, if somewhat predictable, concession was made for the host nation, [Canada](/Canada_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games), which received an automatic qualification spot in every event. This meant that if [Canada](/Canada_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) wasn't already among the top nine, they would simply displace the tenth-ranked nation. If they *were* already in the top nine, the tenth-ranked nation would then get their chance, a small mercy in a system designed for efficiency over sentiment. Each nation was permitted to enter a maximum of one athlete per weight category, ensuring a spread of participation, however thin.

